{
  "What is the formula for calculating pressure?": "",
  "Pressure = Force multiplied by Area": "",
  "Pressure = Force divided by Area": "",
  "Pressure = Area divided by Force": "",
  "Pressure = Mass multiplied by Area": "",
  "Pressure equals force divided by area (P = F/A). The greater the force or the smaller the area, the greater the pressure.": "",
  "What is the SI unit of pressure?": "",
  "Newton": "",
  "Pascal": "",
  "Joule": "",
  "Kelvin": "",
  "The SI unit of pressure is the pascal (Pa). One pascal equals one newton per square meter (1 Pa = 1 N/m^2).": "",
  "If you apply the same force over a smaller area, what happens to the pressure?": "",
  "The pressure stays the same as before": "",
  "The pressure increases proportionally": "",
  "The pressure decreases proportionally": "",
  "The pressure drops down to zero overall": "",
  "Since P = F/A, decreasing the area while keeping force constant will increase the pressure. This is why sharp objects exert more pressure than blunt ones.": "",
  "What does Pascal's principle state about pressure in a confined fluid?": "",
  "Pressure applied to a confined fluid is transmitted equally in all directions": "",
  "Pressure in a fluid decreases as the depth of the fluid increases further": "",
  "Pressure only acts downward in a confined fluid that is not moving at all": "",
  "Pressure in a confined fluid depends only on the temperature of the fluid": "",
  "Pascal's principle states that pressure applied to an enclosed fluid is transmitted undiminished throughout the fluid in all directions.": "",
  "How does water pressure change as you go deeper underwater?": "",
  "It remains constant regardless of depth": "",
  "It decreases as depth gets greater": "",
  "It increases as depth gets greater": "",
  "It fluctuates unpredictably with depth": "",
  "Water pressure increases with depth because there is more water above pushing down. The deeper you go, the greater the weight of water above, and the higher the pressure.": "",
  "A 60 N force is applied over an area of 2 square meters. What is the pressure?": "",
  "120 Pa": "",
  "30 Pa": "",
  "60 Pa": "",
  "15 Pa": "",
  "P = F/A = 60 N / 2 m^2 = 30 Pa. The pressure exerted is 30 pascals.": "",
  "What is atmospheric pressure at sea level approximately equal to?": "",
  "About 10,000 Pa": "",
  "About 101,325 Pa": "",
  "About 500,000 Pa": "",
  "About 1,000,000 Pa": "",
  "Standard atmospheric pressure at sea level is approximately 101,325 Pa (about 101 kPa), which is also called 1 atmosphere (1 atm).": "",
  "What common device operates based on Pascal's principle?": "",
  "A hydraulic car jack or hydraulic lift system": "",
  "A simple lever used to pry open a lid": "",
  "An inclined plane or ramp used for loading": "",
  "A wheel and axle used on a doorknob device": "",
  "Hydraulic systems like car jacks, brakes, and lifts operate based on Pascal's principle. A small force on a small piston creates a large force on a large piston.": "",
  "In a hydraulic system, a small piston has an area of 5 cm^2 and the large piston has an area of 50 cm^2. If you push on the small piston with 10 N, what force is produced at the large piston?": "",
  "50 N": "",
  "100 N": "",
  "200 N": "",
  "500 N": "",
  "By Pascal's principle: F2 = F1 x (A2/A1) = 10 N x (50/5) = 10 x 10 = 100 N. The hydraulic system multiplies the force by a factor of 10.": "",
  "Why do snowshoes help a person walk on deep snow without sinking?": "",
  "They reduce the person's total weight significantly": "",
  "They spread the force over a larger area, reducing pressure": "",
  "They increase friction between the shoe and the snow surface": "",
  "They make the snow underneath become harder and more compacted": "",
  "Snowshoes distribute the person's weight over a larger area. Since P = F/A, increasing the area decreases the pressure on the snow, preventing sinking.": "",
