  "A fluid that is flowing freely through an open channel or pipe system": "",
  "A fluid that is enclosed in a sealed container and cannot escape freely": "",
  "A fluid that has been frozen into a solid state at low temperature levels": "",
  "A fluid that is mixed with another substance to increase its overall density": "",
  "A confined fluid is a liquid or gas enclosed in a sealed container. Pascal's principle applies to confined fluids where pressure changes are transmitted throughout.": "",
  "What does the term 'fluid pressure' mean?": "",
  "The pressure exerted by a fluid on surfaces it is in contact with in all directions": "",
  "The speed at which a fluid flows through a pipe or channel between two points": "",
  "The temperature at which a fluid changes from a liquid state into a gas state": "",
  "The force required to move an object through a fluid from one point to another": "",
  "Fluid pressure is the pressure exerted by a fluid (liquid or gas) on any surface in contact with it. Unlike solids, fluids exert pressure in all directions.": "",
  "What is a piston?": "",
  "A rotating wheel that changes the direction of force through a belt": "",
  "A movable disk or cylinder that fits snugly inside a tube to push fluid": "",
  "A fixed support point around which a lever rotates when force is applied": "",
  "A valve that controls the flow of fluid through a pipe in one direction": "",
  "A piston is a movable component that fits tightly inside a cylinder. When pushed, it exerts pressure on the fluid inside, and the fluid transmits that pressure.": "",
  "What does 'gauge pressure' mean?": "",
  "The total pressure including both fluid pressure and atmospheric pressure": "",
  "The pressure measured relative to atmospheric pressure as a reference": "",
  "The maximum pressure that a container can safely hold without bursting": "",
  "The pressure at the very bottom of a column of fluid in a closed system": "",
  "Gauge pressure is the pressure measured above atmospheric pressure. A tire pressure gauge reads gauge pressure, which is the difference between the tire's internal pressure and the outside air.": "",
  "What does 'hydrostatic pressure' mean?": "",
  "The pressure exerted by a moving fluid as it flows through a narrow pipe": "",
  "The pressure exerted by a fluid at rest due to the weight of fluid above": "",
  "The pressure that builds up when a gas is compressed inside a container": "",
  "The pressure caused by surface tension at the top of a column of liquid": "",
  "Hydrostatic pressure is the pressure at a point in a fluid at rest. It depends on the density of the fluid, gravitational acceleration, and the depth below the surface.": "",
  "What does 'transmitted equally' mean in Pascal's principle?": "",
  "The pressure change spreads evenly throughout all parts of the enclosed fluid": "",
  "The fluid moves at the same speed in every direction inside the container used": "",
  "The temperature of the fluid becomes uniform throughout the whole container": "",
  "Equal amounts of fluid flow out of every opening in the system at all times": "",
  "In Pascal's principle, 'transmitted equally' means that any change in pressure applied to the enclosed fluid is felt throughout the entire fluid without any reduction.": "",
  "A nurse pushes a syringe with 5 N of force. The syringe barrel has an area of 0.5 cm^2. What pressure does the fluid inside the syringe experience?": "",
  "5 N/cm^2": "",
  "10 N/cm^2": "",
  "2.5 N/cm^2": "",
  "15 N/cm^2": "",
  "P = F/A = 5 N / 0.5 cm^2 = 10 N/cm^2. The small area of the syringe tip concentrates the force into a high pressure.": "",
  "A student stands on soft ground wearing regular shoes and then switches to ski boots with a much larger sole. Why do the ski boots prevent sinking?": "",
  "The ski boots are lighter, reducing the total force on the ground surface": "",
  "The larger sole spreads the weight over more area, reducing the pressure": "",
  "The ski boots have better grip, which increases the friction on the ground": "",
  "The ski boots push air under the sole, creating a cushion above the ground": "",
  "Since P = F/A, increasing the contact area (larger sole) while the force (weight) stays the same reduces the pressure on the ground, preventing sinking.": "",
  "A mechanic uses a hydraulic jack where the small piston has an area of 10 cm^2 and the large piston has an area of 200 cm^2. If the mechanic pushes with 50 N on the small piston, what force lifts the car?": "",
  "1,000 N": "",
  "2,000 N": "",
  "5,000 N": "",
  "F2 = F1 x (A2/A1) = 50 N x (200/10) = 50 x 20 = 1,000 N. The hydraulic jack multiplies the mechanic's force by 20.": "",
